(Definition of quetzal from the Cambridge Advanced Learner's Dictionary & Thesaurus © Cambridge University Press)

Examples of quetzal

quetzal

The orange-and-white helicopter descends from the sky like a quetzal from the cloud forest.

The quetzal is one of the most frequently depicted birds in the codices, second only to the eagle.

Both wear the jade mosaic pillbox hat, here ornamented with a small bird and surmounted by a tall crown of green quetzal feathers.

The headdress has a large, predatory bird at the center and many green and red quetzal feathers are fanned out above and beside it.

Some wear back mirrors, but a minority has more elaborate back devices from which fall quetzal feathers.

He could transform into a quetzal or a hummingbird.

One can identify on the tree top a quetzal and a hummingbird, but no nocturnal bird.

Unfortunately for this hypothesis, there are cacti and quetzals in both panels.

Most wear the tezcacuitlapilli back mirror, and only five have a spray of quetzal feathers held by a ribbed ferrule.

However, when pairing with the quetzal, the emblematic nocturnal bird may simply refer to the night and the bird with the long green feathers, to the day.

If the bird in question is a quetzal, the male deities may be wearing the male birds, while the females are wearing the crestless female bird.

The relatively large size of the bird may seem incompatible with the quetzal identification, but this appears to be a costuming convention rather than a statement about the bird's size.

A quetzal is perched in the one corresponding to the east, which is regarded as the region of opulence and moisture.

His crown was a plain golden circle somewhat wider on the forehead than behind, and surmounted with a plume of quetzal-feathers.

The feathers of the quetzal are the ones commonly used in connection with the serpent.
